Intro to Rethinking Package

Jim Albert

7/10/2017

Introduction

Here is a brief introduction to the rethinking package.

library(rethinking)

Specifying a Bayesian Model

We start with a Bayesian model. Using the familiar cars dataset, we fit a simple regresssion model.

\[ y_i \sim N(a + b \, \, x_i), i = 1, ..., n \]

\[ a \sim N(0, 100), b \sim N(0, 10), \sigma \sim unif(0, 50) \] We define a Bayesian model by the alist function.

cars_formula <- alist(
  dist ~ dnorm(mu,sigma),
  mu <- a + b * speed,
  a ~ dnorm(0, 100),
  b ~ dnorm(0, 10),
  sigma ~ dunif(0, 50)
)

Approximate Normal Fit to Posterior

To obtain an approximate normal fit to the posterior, use the map function.

fit1 <- map(cars_formula, data=cars)

The precis function computes basic summaries for each parameter:

precis(fit1)
##         Mean StdDev   5.5% 94.5%
## a     -17.41   6.60 -27.96 -6.85
## b       3.92   0.41   3.27  4.57
## sigma  15.07   1.51  12.66 17.48

The extract.samples function takes a simulated sample from the (approximate) normal posterior.

draws <- extract.samples(fit1)
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(draws, aes(sigma)) +
  geom_density()

Sampling from Exact Posterior

The map2stan implements Hamiltonian sampling using the Stan software.

Again can find summaries and simulated draws by use of the precis and extract.samples functions.

precis(fit2)
##         Mean StdDev lower 0.89 upper 0.89 n_eff Rhat
## a     -16.98   7.24     -27.91      -4.64   297 1.01
## b       3.90   0.45       3.20       4.62   285 1.02
## sigma  15.89   1.69      13.13      18.20   562 1.00
draws2 <- data.frame(extract.samples(fit2))
ggplot(draws2, aes(sigma)) +
  geom_density()

The stancode function shows you the underlying Stan code that is used to define the Bayesian model.

stancode(fit2)
## data{
##     int<lower=1> N;
##     real dist[N];
##     real speed[N];
## }
## parameters{
##     real a;
##     real b;
##     real<lower=0,upper=50> sigma;
## }
## model{
##     vector[N] mu;
##     // sigma ~ uniform( 0 , 50 );
##     b ~ normal( 0 , 10 );
##     a ~ normal( 0 , 100 );
##     for ( i in 1:N ) {
##         mu[i] = a + b * speed[i];
##     }
##     dist ~ normal( mu , sigma );
## }
## generated quantities{
##     vector[N] mu;
##     real dev;
##     dev = 0;
##     for ( i in 1:N ) {
##         mu[i] = a + b * speed[i];
##     }
##     dev = dev + (-2)*normal_lpdf( dist | mu , sigma );
## }

The plot method will show trace plots for the simulated draws for each parameter.

plot(fit2)

Posterior of Linear Components

Suppose we are interested in learning about the linear component \[ a + b \, \, x \] for particular values of the covariate x.

I define three values of the speeds of interest.

new_data <- data.frame(speed = c(10, 15, 20))

The link function simulates values of the linear component for each value of x. The output is a data frame with 1000 rows and 3 columns. I use the apply function to find a 80 percent probability interval for each linear component.

sim_parameters <- link(fit2, data=new_data)
## [ 100 / 1000 ]
[ 200 / 1000 ]
[ 300 / 1000 ]
[ 400 / 1000 ]
[ 500 / 1000 ]
[ 600 / 1000 ]
[ 700 / 1000 ]
[ 800 / 1000 ]
[ 900 / 1000 ]
[ 1000 / 1000 ]
apply(sim_parameters, 2, quantile, c(.1, .9))
##         [,1]     [,2]     [,3]
## 10% 17.86428 38.49959 57.11346
## 90% 26.28109 44.53425 65.17667

Predictions

Instead suppose we are interested in learning about the future response for selected values of x. The sim function simulates from the posterior predictive distribution of future response y. I use apply to find 80 percent prediction intervals.

sim_predictions <- sim(fit2, data=new_data)
## [ 100 / 1000 ]
[ 200 / 1000 ]
[ 300 / 1000 ]
[ 400 / 1000 ]
[ 500 / 1000 ]
[ 600 / 1000 ]
[ 700 / 1000 ]
[ 800 / 1000 ]
[ 900 / 1000 ]
[ 1000 / 1000 ]
apply(sim_predictions, 2, quantile, c(.1, .9))
##          [,1]     [,2]     [,3]
## 10%  2.187249 22.66024 40.38659
## 90% 42.142376 61.09810 80.62289
